Review: ay almodóvar… que vamos a hacer contigo

Some of the most inspired shot composition I’ve ever seen in here… every time the camera moves away from a close-up to reveal another character in the frame… just incredible. The first half of this is an all-timer for me, the second half is of significantly less interest but it’s clear Antonioni is much more interested in establishing atmosphere than plot, and the conclusion is as cathartic as it could be anyway.

an excellent addition to the dad movie canon

he’s dumb as rocks, she’s barbra streisand. a match made in heaven, a perfect screwball comedy! just one delightful & hilarious scene after the other, back to back, culminating in an incredible set piece consisting of a multi-car chase through the streets of san francisco. loved!

watching this feels almost equivalent to watching the birth of cinema. the whole thing moves with an incredible sense of musicality, each cut contextualized and redefined by the ones that came before and after it. the never-ending montages rhythmically paced, building on top of each other. just incredible!
everyone in this movie is so aggressively fit/skinny i started getting scared

ridiculously overstuffed (seriously, they tried, and did, fit a whole season into this), but i don’t know how you could love the series and not at the very least enjoy this. i love these four women dearly, and that’s all i really need from a sex and the city movie. ….the good: the vivienne westwood wedding dress, charlotte’s pregnancy, new york, mr big ultimately proposing with a manolo blahnik, louise and meet me in st. louis (which, weird addition,…

When we first meet Bella Baxter, she is a captive. In her house, in her surroundings, in her own body. Her actions are unconscious to her, a woman with a child’s brain. Her will is repressed, something greater than she can understand, even as she feels the need to reach it. When we leave Bella Baxter, she is in a situation and place reached purely by her agency. The journey that lies in between is delightfully delirious and uncomfortably weird,…
